    <h4>Chronology & Movable Feasts</h4>

    <p>
      The chronology of the Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church is counted from the
      <strong>Birth of Our Lord Jesus Christ</strong>, known as the <em>Era of Incarnation</em>.
      Because of this ancient reckoning, the Ethiopian calendar differs from the Gregorian calendar
      by <strong>7 or 8 years</strong>, depending on the month.
    </p>

    <p>
      The calculation of <strong>Easter (Fasika)</strong> — the center of all movable feasts —
      follows the traditional system of <strong>Ammonius</strong>, a method preserved by the Church
      for centuries.
    </p>
  </div>

<div class="festivals-box">
  <h5 class="festivals-title">Rules for Movable Feasts</h5>
  <ul class="festivals-list">

      <li><strong>Easter Lent:</strong> Begins on a Monday (between Yekatit 1 – Megabit 5).</li>
      <li><strong>Palm Sunday:</strong> Between Megabit 19 – Miyazia 23.</li>
      <li><strong>Easter (Fasika):</strong> Always a Sunday (between Megabit 26 – Miyazia 30).</li>
      <li><strong>Ascension:</strong> Always a Thursday.</li>
      <li><strong>Pentecost:</strong> Always a Sunday.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

